T 1259":"omkring 1259","1293":"1293","1280":"1280","Cochwillan, Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Cochwillan, Caernarfonshire, Wales","Llaniestyn, Anglesey, Wales":"Llaniestyn, Anglesey, Wales",",,Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"ABT 1259–":"circa 1259–Overleden","1259–1310":"1259–1310","1279–1320":"1279–1320","1280–1375":"1280–1375","–Male":"Overleden","1293–Female":"1293–Overleden","1259–Female":"1259–Overleden","1259":"1259","1279":"1279","1310":"1310","1375":"1375","1320":"1320","ABT 1259":"circa 1259","1293":"1293","1280":"1280","Cochwillan, Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Cochwillan, Caernarfonshire, Wales","Llaniestyn, Anglesey, Wales":"Llaniestyn, Anglesey, Wales",",,Wales":"Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"ABT 1259–":"about 1259–Deceased","1259–1310":"1259–1310","1279–1320":"1279–1320","1280–1375":"1280–1375","–Male":"Deceased","1293–Female":"1293–Deceased","1259–Female":"1259–Deceased","1259":"1259","1279":"1279","1310":"1310","1375":"1375","1320":"1320","ABT 1259":"about 1259","1293":"1293","1280":"1280","Cochwillan, Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Cochwillan, Caernarfonshire, Wales","Llaniestyn, Anglesey, Wales":"Llaniestyn, Anglesey, Wales",",,Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tudor","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: from the personal name <i>Tudur</i>, a derivative of British Celtic <i>Toutorīx</i>, literally ‘people’ + ‘king’. It has sometimes been taken as a Welsh equivalent of Latin <i>Theodorus</i>, from Greek <i>Theodōros</i> ‘gift of God’ (see   Theodore  ), for which the usual Welsh form is <i>Tewdwr</i>.","Romanian and Croatian: from the personal name <i>Tudor</i>, a variant of <i>Teodor</i> (see   Theodore  ).","History: The Tudor royal family, English sovereigns from the accession of Henry VII in 1485 to the death of Elizabeth I in 1603, were of Welsh origin, being descended from Owain ap Maredudd ap Tudur, who held lands at Penmynydd in Anglesey."],"variants":[{"name":"Tutor","meanings":["Probably Welsh: variant of   Tudor  ."]},{"name":"Theodore","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Serge, Henri, Pierre, Alide, Andre, Antoine, Benoit, Berthony, Chantal, Daphnee, Edouard, Guilene.","French and Mauritian (<b>Théodore</b>); West Indian (in Haiti, Martinique, and Guadeloupe <b>Théodore</b>); English and Welsh: from a personal name derived from Greek <i>Theodōros</i>, a compound of <i>theos</i> ‘God’ + <i>dōron</i> ‘gift’, which was relatively popular in the Middle Ages because of its auspicious meaning. The name was borne by several early Christian saints. There was considerable confusion with the ancient Germanic name <i>Theodoric</i> (see   Terry  ). In Wales, the personal name <i>Theodore</i> was also adopted as an approximation to the Welsh name <i>Tewdwr</i> (see   Tudor  ). In North America, this surname has absorbed various other European cognates and their derivatives, e.g. Greek   Theodorakis  , Macedonian <b>Todorovski</b>, and Serbian <b>Todorović</b> (see   Todorovic  )."]},{"name":"Tedder","meanings":["English (Surrey): from the Middle English personal name <i>Thedere</i>, <i>Teddere</i>, which is either from the Old English personal name <i>Thēodhere</i> (from <i>thēod</i> ‘people’ + <i>here</i> ‘army’) or from the cognate ancient Germanic personal name <i>Theudher</i>, which seems to have been adopted by the Normans. Alternatively, perhaps it may be an occupational name from Middle English <i>teddere</i> ‘one who teds’, i.e. a person whose occupation was to spread mown grass for drying.","Welsh: variant of   Tudor  ."]}]},{"name":"Gruffydd","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Welsh: The Welsh name; from creffydd, strong faith, or strong in faith. Gruffydd, a Welsh form of Gryffydd."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Gruffydd Ap Tudor was born about 1259, in Wales, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Gruffyd ap Tudor ap Madog ap Lard